President Muhammadu Buhari has called on judicial officers to work towards the creation of special courts to assist in the speedy administration and dispensation of justice in the country.  Speaking Monday in Abuja at the opening ceremony of the 2019 biennial All Nigeria Judges Conference of Superior Courts, President Buhari who noted the challenges facing the judiciary, said the government has been committed to a number of justice sector reforms such as enhancement of judicial budgetary allocations, review of extant laws and enactment of new laws that will improve the lives of Nigerians.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that President Buhari also commended the dedication of the judiciary in the timely dispensation of electoral disputes and urged them to do more. The Chief Justice of Nigeria, Justice Ibrahim Tanko Muhammad assured continuous reforms in the judicial system to enable quick dispensation of justice.  Meanwhile, President Muhammadu Buhari has said the rehabilitation of internally displaced persons (IDPs) in the country is urgent and imperative, if it would not constitute a big problem to the country in future. The President who spoke at State House, Abuja, while receiving in audience the President of the 74th United Nations General Assembly, Nigeria’s Professor Tijjani Muhammad-Bande urged the UN General Assembly President to make Nigeria’s challenges glaring to the world.  President Buhari said Nigeria was committed to education, and providing health care to the young and old, among other policies. Prof. Muhammad-Bande briefing State House correspondent after meeting Mr President expressed appreciation to President Buhari for the support given, leading to his emergence as UNGA President, and the continued cooperation from Nigeria.